{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17499343","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17499343"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T09:58:50+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T09:58:50+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1488"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1488","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1488"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.11,0.05,0.33,0.01,0.51]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1488"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"75847"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1488","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1488"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1488"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61360"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"5"},{"type":"tags","id":"14"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"92"},{"type":"tags","id":"4964"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"1446"},{"type":"contributions","id":"1478"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43847"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"75847","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/75847"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 48-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic for an insurance medical check. He has a history of hepatitis B infection diagnosed 10 years ago prior to migration to Australia, for which he did not receive treatment. He has no other significant medical history and takes no regular medications. He drinks two cans of beer per weekend and is a non-smoker.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well with vital signs within normal limits. Abdominal examination is unremarkable with no hepatomegaly or stigmata of chronic liver disease.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EInvestigations reveal:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003EHepatitis B surface antigen: positive\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EHepatitis B surface antibody: negative\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EHepatitis B core antibody IgG: positive\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EHepatitis B viral load: \u0026lt;200 IU/mL\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003ELiver function tests within normal limits\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EFull blood count within normal limits\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EUrea, electrolytes and creatinine within normal limits\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate management plan?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Hepatitis B vaccination","Immediate cessation of alcohol","Start antiviral medications","Liver biopsy","Six-monthly liver function tests and fibroscan"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient has chronic hepatitis B infection in the immune control phase, characterised by positive HBsAg, positive anti-HBc IgG, low viral load (\u0026lt;200 IU/mL), and normal liver function tests. The immune control phase occurs after the immune clearance phase, where the immune system has successfully suppressed viral replication. The table below for further interpretation of serological results.  Certain patients who are at higher risk of developing hepatocellular carcinoma (HCC) require 6-monthly ultrasounds as well - these include patients with existing cirrhosis, with family history of HCC, Aboriginal and Torres Straight Islander people over 50 years of age and sub-African people over 20 years of age. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESix-monthly liver function tests and fibroscan \u003C/strong\u003Elifelong is the most appropriate management. Despite good viral control, regular monitoring is essential as the previous immune clearance phase may have caused liver damage, and there remains a risk of hepatocellular carcinoma. This surveillance allows early detection of disease progression.  Treatment is based on patient symptoms, liver function tests and viral load - given that the patient has a relatively low viral load and normal liver function tests, then no active treatment is required apart from monitoring.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EStart antiviral medications\u003C/strong\u003E is not indicated in this phase of infection. Antiviral therapy should be considered if there is evidence of active disease (ALT elevation or viral load \u0026gt;2000 IU/mL). Current options include entecavir and tenofovir.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHepatitis B vaccination\u003C/strong\u003E would be ineffective as the patient is already infected with the virus. Vaccination is only useful for prevention in unexposed individuals.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EImmediate cessation of alcohol\u003C/strong\u003E is unnecessarily restrictive. Small amounts of alcohol consumption within national guidelines is acceptable in patients with well-controlled chronic hepatitis B who do not have advanced fibrosis or cirrhosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELiver biopsy\u003C/strong\u003E is not required for diagnosis or monitoring in this case. Non-invasive monitoring with fibroscan and blood tests is sufficient for surveillance and such an invasive test would not add to his management plan.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Chronic hepatitis B in the immune control phase (low viral load, normal LFTs) does not require antiviral therapy","Regular monitoring with 6-monthly LFTs and fibroscans is essential even in well-controlled hepatitis B","Antiviral therapy should be considered if ALT becomes elevated or viral load exceeds 2000 IU/mL"],"references":["Hepatitis Australia Contributors, 2019. Hepatitis B Treatment. Access at: https://www.hepatitisaustralia.com/hepatitis-b-treatment.","Towell, V \u0026 Cowie, B, 2012. Hepatitis B Serology. RACGP. Access at: https://www.racgp.org.au/afp/2012/april/hepatitis-b-serology/.","Australian STI Management Guidelines. Decision Making in Hepatitis B. ASHM. 2024.  Available at: http://ashm.org.au/resources/decision-making-in-hepatitis-b/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61360"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1488"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"1541"}]}}},{"type":"media","id":"1541","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/1541"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/8deeda41-45c1-4128-a021-d59cbd0aa719.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/8deeda41-45c1-4128-a021-d59cbd0aa719.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":456,"height":190}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61360","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/61360"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-01T00:14:29+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-01T00:14:30+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1488"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"75847"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"5","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/5"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2d","name":"Gastroenterology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"14","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/14"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udda0","name":"Infectious Diseases","synonyms":["ID"],"descr